INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '5521f7be-9083-477d-83a8-6a213ec54599',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Django's Batteries-Included Admin: Customizing Beyond the Defaults$escape$,
  $escape$Django's admin isn't just a CRUD scaffold — it's a fully extensible framework. Most developers stop at `list_display` and `search_fields`, but the real power lies in `ModelAdmin` hooks and inline formsets.

`list_select_related` prevents N+1 queries when displaying related fields. `get_queryset()` lets you scope data per-user without touching views. `save_model()` lets you inject business logic at save time — perfect for audit trails or triggering signals without duplicating service logic.

Inlines (`TabularInline`, `StackedInline`) let you edit related models on the same page. Combine with `extra = 0` and `can_delete = False` for tight UX control.

`readonly_fields` can point to callables, letting you render computed properties or formatted HTML directly in the change view — no template override needed.

For bulk operations, `actions` accepts callables with `(modeladmin, request, queryset)` signatures, giving you queryset-level control with full ORM access. Add `@admin.action(description='...')` for clean labeling.

The admin is production-grade tooling if you treat it like code, not config.$escape$,
  $escape$@admin.register(Order)
class OrderAdmin(admin.ModelAdmin):
    list_display = ('id', 'user', 'status', 'total_display')
    list_select_related = ('user',)
    readonly_fields = ('created_at', 'total_display')
    actions = ['mark_fulfilled']

    def get_queryset(self, request):
        qs = super().get_queryset(request)
        if not request.user.is_superuser:
            return qs.filter(assigned_to=request.user)
        return qs

    @admin.display(description='Total')
    def total_display(self, obj):
        return f'${obj.total:.2f}'

    @admin.action(description='Mark selected orders as fulfilled')
    def mark_fulfilled(self, request, queryset):
        queryset.update(status='fulfilled')$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
